<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1894-01-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1894-01-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="710" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d710">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Uhl</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Terrell</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Department
                                        of State</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1894-01-04"><hi rend="italic">January 4,
                                1894</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 113.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received your No. 106, of November
                            15 last, regarding the presumed issue of a notice “that the Porte will
                            require that all conveyances of land to foreign subjects shall hereafter
                            contain a clause prohibiting the use of the property for schools or
                            religious worship.”</p>
                        <p>Noting your statement that you have addressed a written notice to the
                            Porte that you reserve the right to protest hereafter against this
                            requirement,</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Edwin P. Uhl</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>